         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Ballina. ¶  31 May. 78. ¶ My dear Baron ¶  ¶ This Evening I received your double communications of 19th &amp; 20th Inst: and, as our local papers (2) are published on Friday and Saturday, your letter for ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">78.05.31</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From Charles Fawcett</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M7, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS found with a specimen of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Bulbophyllum%20minutissimum">Bulbophyllum minutissimum</name>
                     </seg> (MEL 1540829).</p>
               </note>Ballina.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>NSW.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> 31 May. 78.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Baron</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>This Evening I received your double communications of 19th &amp; 20th Inst: and, as our local papers (2) are published on Friday and Saturday, your letter for publication cannot appear until the end of next week.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Letter of 19 May not found; See M to C Fawcett, 20 May 1878, the notes to which contain details of publication of that letter in the two local newspapers. </p>
               </note> There was no danger of my sending specimens to anyone but yourself, at least until after you had described it; if, even then. By this post I hope you will receive safely a packet with a good fresh specimen of your B. m.,<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Bulbophyllum%20minutissimum">Bulbophyllum minutissimum</name>
                     </seg>; see M to C Fawcett, 20 May 1878.</p>
               </note> some mosses, &amp;c. You will easily recognize the mosses from the same tree as the orchid. The others came from an oak (swamp) and a <name key="Hybiscus">Hybiscus</name>.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Hibiscus?</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> The roots of all those trees are splashed by salt water (on the banks of North Creek, Ballina. The tree, on which the B. m., is a nephelium, I presume; and, on a <name key="Cupania">Cupania</name> not far off, the B. m. appears again, but more sparingly. Nowhere else could I find it. Pray let me have the name of the fern or ferns accompanying. The short leaves &amp; the long ones appear to differ &amp; came from separate trees, oaks. I fancy you could get this <name key="Dendrobium">Dendrobium</name> to flower by laying the bark in a dish on wet sand. In any case, if the packet goes safe, you could describe it with the fruit and wait for the flower — as some of the fruit appears quite fresh — The tree leans over the water, and, while I was away lately, some Goth cut <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">half of it</hi>
               </seg> off, from <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">which</hi>
               </seg> I cut the present specimen. The ferns to which I refer are wrapped with the Bark — There are two other ferns, in paper, numbered. If the seed of the <name key="Didiscus">Didiscus</name> is not sufficiently ripe let me know. I send also olax specimens — Would any one you know take the trouble of experimenting on our native tobacco Seed? If so, I could send some fresh seed — I dried a few leaves and the flavour reminded me of the Havanas of my early days — I don't smoke now — I shall send copies of the papers.<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>A cutting from the </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Richmond River express and Tweed advertiser</seg> is with MEL 1540829.</p>
               </note> With best wishes, I am, My dear Baron,</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">yours truly</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Charles. H. Fawcett:</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Baron Ferd von Mueller.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>&amp;c<space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>&amp;c<space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>&amp;c.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">P.S. The narrow leaved <name key="Melothria%20">Melothria </name>is never seen up the river —</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
